Upon analyzing the current solution, I see a mistake in the way that the number of purple squares is calculated. The calculation `purpleSquares += std::min(horizontal[J], L);` is incorrect because it does not consider the starting row `R` of the vertical street. It assumes all vertical streets start from the first row, which is not always the case, hence it may count extra purple squares that do not exist.

To fix this, I will maintain a frequency array for each column that stores the number of horizontal streets occupying each cell. For the vertical streets, I will need to iterate from the starting row `R` to `R + L - 1` and count the purple squares.

Here's the corrected solution:

```cpp
#include <fstream>
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::ifstream fin("pergament.in");
    std::ofstream fout("pergament.out");

    int N, K, Q, A, B, C, D;
    fin >> N >> K >> Q >> A >> B >> C >> D;

    // Create a 2D vector to store the number of horizontal streets occupying each cell.
    std::vector<std::vector<int>> horizontal(K + 1, std::vector<int>(N + 1, 0));
    int X, Y;
    fin >> X >> Y;

    for (int i = 1; i <= N; ++i) {
        for (int j = X; j < X + Y; ++j) {
            horizontal[j][i] = 1;
        }
        if (i < N) {
            X = 1 + (1LL * X * A + B) % K;
            Y = 1 + (1LL * Y * C + D) % (K - X + 1);
        }
    }

    int J, R, L, purpleSquares = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < Q; ++i) {
        fin >> J >> R >> L;
        for (int j = R; j < R + L && j <= N; ++j) {
            purpleSquares += horizontal[J][j];
        }
    }

    fout << purpleSquares << '\n';

    return 0;
}
```

This solution uses a 2D vector `horizontal` to record the presence of horizontal streets in each cell of the pergament. When reading vertical streets, it now correctly counts the number of purple squares by considering the starting point `R` of the vertical street and its length `L`.

Please note that this solution might have a higher memory consumption due to the use of a 2D vector, but it's necessary to track the cells occupied by horizontal streets. Since `K <= 50`, the maximum size of the `horizontal` vector will be `50 * 10000000`, which should fit in memory.
